[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Luke 14:25-27",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 14:25-27",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And there went great multitudes with him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— It seems they accompanied him from place to place, with eager desire, doubtless, to have the Messiah’s kingdom erected; proposing to themselves all manner of wealth and temporal advantage therein. One day, therefore, as they were on the road with him, he thought fit to show them plainly their mistake: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he turned and said, If any man come to me, and hate not, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — As all the hopes of temporal felicity under his reign, which his disciples entertained, were to be blasted; as he himself was to suffer an ignominious death; and as they were to be exposed unto all manner of persecutions, he declared publicly to the multitude, that, if they proposed to be his disciples, it was absolutely necessary that they should prefer his service to every thing in the world, and by their conduct show that they hated father, and mother, and wife, and children, that is to say, loved the dearest objects of their affections less than him. As in this, so in several other passages of Scripture, the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hatred ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "signifies only an inferior degree of love. Father and mother, and other relations, are particularly mentioned by our Lord, because, as matters then stood, the profession of the gospel was apt to set a man at variance with his nearest relations. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Whosoever doth not bear his cross, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — See on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 10:37-38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
